VARIABLES AND VALUES:-
# All the contents we write in JavaScript are considered as Strings and are written using double quotes. 
# For displaying the numbers we can write the contents without using the double quotes.
# let is used to declare a variable  with block scope.
 It can be reassigned but not redeclared.
# var can be used to declare a variable with function scope.
 It can be redeclared and reassigned.
# const can be used to declare a variable with block scope.
 It must be initialized at declaration and cannot be reassigned. But if it's an array or object its contents can still be modified.
# The naming of the variables should always begin with letters also camelcasing should be taken care of i.e; names of the variable should be linke this: myFriend.


DATATYPES IN JAVASCRIPT:-
Primitive-type Datatypes:- BigInt, number, string, boolean, null, undefined, symbol.
# Numbers can be written just as it is and the string components can be written inside "cjdfhu".
# We can find the type of the variable by the following format typeof<space>variblename.
# If we define a variable with no values then the type of that variable will be undefined.
# To note that a variable has no value for that particluar variable then we'll be able to make it by giving the value = null
# Normally, there will be a limit for entering the values like numbers, here we can define the variable as 
 let num = BigInt(1234567890)   and the typeof this will be bigint.
# Boolean is a datatype that stores 2 values: true and false.
# Symbol is also another data type in JS that is not mostly used.

Reference-type Datatypes:- Object, Array, function.
# Object datatype can be used to store the details of a particular person and so on.
  For example to store the details of a person, we can use the object as follows:
 const person = {
  name: "Akhil" , 
  age:23,
  married:true
}
# Array datatype can be used to store a list of items such as marks of the subjects and so on.
 For example to store the marks of a student scored:
 const marks = ["Akhil", "Manoj", "Subha"]

# The main difference between the primitive and reference type dataype is that in Primitive datatypes the actual value is stored and in reference type the address
 or reference of the data is stored.
# For object datatypes, it can be delcared as let obj1 = {
 name: :John",
 age: 30
}
 This is an object with the name obj1. The output will be as follows:  { name: 'John', age: 30 }
 To print only the name then we'll write console.log(obj1.name) Output will be John.

